Jarkell Ravensteel<br>
Scout of Kelethin <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uwendartruespirit.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wendar Truespirit</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/5/02 2:20:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23090.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Tracking</span><hr size=1> Speaking from the class balancing standpoint, rogues should not get tracking. Rogues are one class that doesn't need to be bumped up to be as powerful as other classes. You have backstab, hide/sneak, etc... Sure, I can understand you wanting it to track PC's or huminode mobs, etc... but that doesn't mean you SHOULD have it. Tracking indoors only allows you to know if a mob is up. Period. Especially with multiple floors. Why should you have that ability over another class (meaning warriors, monks, etc..)? In the outdoors, why should you have the ability, class balancing wise, to know if a pc or npc is up nearby? You shouldn't. This is an ability of rangers, and to an extent druids and bards.<br>
<br>
Speaking from a RPing standpoint, it greatly depends on what you think a rogue is. What I see the EQ rogue as is, thief out of combat, assassin in combat. All of your out of combat skills are more of a theif (hide/sneak, pickpocket, etc...). Your in combat skills; backstab and evade (yes I know it's just the Hide button), are more assassin like. If you try to say, &quot;An EQ rogue is an assassin.&quot; or &quot;An EQ rogue is a theif.&quot; you're going to be wrong. They are a mixture of the two, and if you think of it the way I discribed, it might make more sense to you why you get the skills you do, and not the skills you don't.<br>
<br>
Taking away from RPing for the sake of balance is very fundamental in EQ. For example, rangers should be using their bow for most melee damage. But they don't (save having the AA skills, and only in specific circumstances). The reason? The range reduces the aggro you recieve from dealing out damage. Casters get away with it because they have a limited supply of mana. Rangers can easily get an endless supply of arrows (Endless Quiver, or Tolan's Darkwood Bracer). For the sake of class balance, using a bow for main damage output is only allowed aside from in a few select circumstances.<br>
<br>
To get back on topic, to give a rogue tracking because it makes sense in some definitions of what a rogue is would be like giving any class the chance to kill any mob in a single shot at every level. RPing wise it makes sense right? It's certainly possible to cut a head in a single shot. But you don't, because while RPing wise, it may make sense, it doesn't work well in EQ.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
